                                          CHAPTER 1, NDOS FEATURES
___________________________________________________________________


CHAPTER 1, NDOS FEATURES


NDOS is a complete computing environment that works with all
versions of MS-DOS and PC-DOS from 2.0 to 6; with DR-DOS 3.4, 5.0,
and above.  It is compatible with virtually all application
programs, with Microsoft Windows, and with task switching programs
like DESQview and Back & Forth.

NDOS replaces the traditional DOS user interface with a more
modern, friendlier, and more powerful one.  NDOS is completely
compatible with traditional DOS commands, and adds dozens of new
features that aren't available with any version of DOS.


    Minimal Memory Usage

    NDOS can take advantage of extended memory, expanded memory,
    and memory managers for 80286, 386, and 486 systems.  If you
    load both NDOS and the environment "high," NDOS will use only
    448 bytes of base memory, less than any version of the
    traditional DOS command processor, COMMAND.COM (see page
    117).


    Online Help

    NDOS has complete, full-screen, context-sensitive help for all
    of its commands and all DOS utilities.  The F1 key pops up the
    help system at any time from the NDOS prompt.  The help system
    is cross-referenced and includes examples (see page 55).


    Directory Navigation

    You can specify where to look for subdirectories with the NDOS
    enhanced CD command.  CDD lets you switch drives and
    directories simultaneously, and the new automatic directory
    change feature changes directories for you when you type a
    directory name at the command line.


    Faster and Better Batch Files

    NDOS speeds up traditional DOS batch files, and introduces a
    new kind of batch file processing that is five to ten times
    faster than traditional batch files as well (see page 91).



___________________________________________________________________
NDOS Reference Manual                                            5

                                          CHAPTER 1, NDOS FEATURES
___________________________________________________________________

    In addition, NDOS has more than two dozen new batch file
    commands, and many other enhancements that will make your
    batch files easier to write and far more powerful.


    Command Line Enhancements

    NDOS replaces the traditional command line with a much
    friendlier and more powerful command line environment.  Among
    the features which NDOS offers are:

         Command Line Editing:  You can use the cursor keys to
         make corrections, in the same way that you would with a
         text editor (see page 48).

         Command History and Recall:  NDOS keeps track of each
         command you type.  You can recall any command and issue
         it again, or edit it to create a slightly different
         command.   Commands can be recalled one at a time, or you
         can pop up a window of recently entered commands and
         choose the one you want (see page 49).

         Automatic Filename Expansion:  If you type part of a
         filename, with or without wildcards, NDOS will fill in
         the complete filename for you at the touch of a key
         (see page 52).

         Multiple Commands on a Single Line:  You can type a
         series of commands on a single line instead of waiting
         for each one to finish before you issue the next one
         (see page 54).

         Multiple Filenames:  Most NDOS commands can operate on
         multiple files at once.  For example, you can copy
         several files at once from your hard drive to drive A:
         with a command like:

              copy *.wks *.dat *.txt  a:\

         Point-and-Shoot File Selection:  The SELECT command lets
         you choose files with the cursor keys instead of
         remembering their names.  It gives you a full "point-and-
         shoot" environment for other NDOS commands (see page
         275).


    Aliases

    An alias is a command you create, assigned to a name you
    select or to a key combination of your choosing.  You can use

___________________________________________________________________
NDOS Reference Manual                                            6

                                          CHAPTER 1, NDOS FEATURES
___________________________________________________________________

    aliases to rename commands, to set command defaults, and to
    create new commands that are a combination of other commands.
    When aliases are combined with the NDOS multiple command
    feature, they act like very fast batch files (see pages 88
    and 159).


    File Descriptions

    NDOS lets you assign a description (up to 40 characters long)
    to each of your files and directories.  The descriptions are
    displayed with the DIR and SELECT commands, and move with
    their files when you use a COPY, DEL, MOVE, or RENAME command
    (see page 193).


    Executable Extensions

    Executable extensions let you associate a file extension with
    the program that processes files of that type.  For example,
    you could associate .BAS files with the BASIC interpreter, or
    .DBF files with dBASE or Foxbase.  NDOS runs the appropriate
    program automatically whenever you type the name of a file
    that has an extension you have defined as executable (see
    page 68).


    Compatibility

    You can use NDOS:

         *  with all monochrome, CGA, EGA, and VGA video systems,
            with any number of screen rows and columns.

         *  with DOS-compatible networks, including Novell Netware,
            Microsoft LAN Manager, Banyan Vines, and Artisoft
            LANTastic.

         *  with all popular memory managers and task switchers.

         *  with virtually all commercial applications, utility
            programs, and memory-resident utilities (TSRs).


    New Commands and Options

    NDOS includes over 80 commands.  A few are the same as
    traditional commands.  Many are compatible with traditional
    commands but are enhanced with several additional options.
    The majority are unique to NDOS.  If you have always wished

___________________________________________________________________
NDOS Reference Manual                                            7

                                          CHAPTER 1, NDOS FEATURES
___________________________________________________________________

    that DOS had a command to help in a special situation, you
    will probably find that command in NDOS.  A complete list of
    NDOS commands and options, along with explanations of how to
    use them, begins on page 153.















































