                                                    Installing NDOS
___________________________________________________________________


CHAPTER 2, INSTALLATION


Before you install NDOS (or any other software, for that matter),
you should make a bootable system floppy disk so you can recover
in case of a power failure or other interruption during the
installation process.  Put a blank floppy disk in drive A:, then
type:

         format a: /s

Once the process is complete, test your bootable floppy disk by
leaving it in drive A: and simultaneously pressing the Ctrl, Alt,
and Del keys to make sure your system boots properly.  After
that, put the floppy disk away in a safe place and reboot your
computer normally.

To install NDOS while installing the Norton Utilities:

1 Follow the instructions in the "Norton Utilities User's Guide,"
  Chapter 1, "Installation." When you reach Step 6 of "To install
  Norton Utilities," select Custom Installation.

  A screen appears where you can choose a directory to install
  Norton Utilities.

2 Select a directory to install Norton Utilities.

3 Continue to follow the installation instructions in Chapter 1
  until you come to the section, "To select which Norton Utilities
  programs to install," then select NDOS from the programs list on
  this screen.

  NDOS installs using the defaults when Norton Utilities installs.

To install NDOS after installing Norton Utilities:

1 At the DOS prompt, type NUCONFIG.

  The Norton Utilities Configuration dialog box appears.

2 Select Startup Programs from the dialog box.

3 Select NDOS from the Startup Programs list box.

4 Select the Configure command button or double-click NDOS.

  The NDOS configuration dialog box appears. From this dialog box
  you can install NDOS as well as configure many NDOS options.


___________________________________________________________________
NDOS Reference Manual                                            9

                                                  Uninstalling NDOS
___________________________________________________________________

5 Check the Load Command Processor Into Upper Memory check box and
  select OK.

6 Select OK from the Startup Programs dialog box.

7 Select Quit from the Norton Utilities Configuration dialog box.

  A message pops up suggesting that you reboot to activate NDOS
  immediately.

8 Select reboot.


##  Uninstalling NDOS

    In the extremely unlikely event that you have trouble booting
    your computer after you install NDOS, you can also remove it
    quite easily.  We don't expect you to have any trouble, but we
    know some people feel more comfortable knowing how to
    uninstall a product as well as install it.  Or, you may need
    to remove NDOS from one system if you are moving it to another
    system.

    To temporarily remove NDOS from your system, first note the
    location of COMMAND.COM on your disk (for example, in the root
    directory, or the DOS directory).  Boot the system and use any
    text editor to edit your CONFIG.SYS file (before modifying
    CONFIG.SYS be sure you have a bootable floppy disk as
    discussed above).  Look for a line that begins:

         SHELL=D:\PATH\NDOS.COM ...

    ("d:\path" means a drive letter and directory name).  Insert
    the characters "REM " at the beginning of this line.  This
    converts it into "remarks" or comments.  (If you are using DOS
    3, REMarks are not recognized in CONFIG.SYS, so the changed
    lines will produce a harmless "Unrecognized command" error
    when the system boots.)  Next, add a new line like this:

         SHELL=D:\PATH\COMMAND.COM /P

    where "d:\path" is the proper drive and directory for
    COMMAND.COM.  If you were previously running COMMAND.COM with
    a /E:nnnn switch to set the size of your environment, you can
    add it to this line as well.

    After CONFIG.SYS has been modified, edit your AUTOEXEC.BAT
    file to remove any changes made to accommodate NDOS.  Look for
    two commands:


___________________________________________________________________
NDOS Reference Manual                                           10

                                                  Uninstalling NDOS
___________________________________________________________________

         SET COMSPEC=D:\PATH\NDOS.COM
         D:\PATH\KSTACK.COM

    The first command will not be present on most systems.  If
    it's there, change it to read:

         SET COMSPEC=D:\PATH\COMMAND.COM

    where "d:\path" is replaced by the correct drive and directory
    for COMMAND.COM.  The second command can be deleted, or you
    can place "REM " in front of it to convert it to a comment.
    The second command may be present without the "d:\path"
    portion or the ".COM" portion; the key thing to look for is
    "KSTACK".  If you wish, you can look for the PATH command, and
    remove the NDOS directory from the directories listed there.
    However, there's probably no reason to do so unless you're
    permanently removing NDOS from your system.

    Now reboot your system, and you should be back up and running
    under COMMAND.COM.  Correct the problem that gave you trouble
    with NDOS (contact our technical support department if you
    need help).  Once the problem is fixed, edit your CONFIG.SYS
    file again to remove the REMs on your NDOS lines and put one
    on your COMMAND.COM line instead, restore any COMSPEC command
    in AUTOEXEC.BAT, and you can boot with NDOS again.


























